<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12088h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12088h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12088h"> 88(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hornbook</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">To Master John, the Chamber-maid / A Horn-Book gives of Ginger-bread; / And, that the Child may learn the better, / As he can name, he eats the Letter. <small> Edward FitzGerald, <a name="EFMI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EFMI"><cite title="source">Miscellanies</cite></a> (1900) 99</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n20001c" href="n20all.htm#n20001c">N20 (VI.B.13):001(c)</a>. A hornbook is an early form of child&apos;s primer, usually consisting of the alphabet, the ten digits and the Lord&apos;s Prayer, written on a sheet of paper encased in a protective covering of translucent horn. </mm> </dd></dl>
